The proposed Arapahoe Station and Village Center developments are located along the east
side of Fiddlers Green Circle just north of Peakview Avenue in Greenwood Village, Colorado.
I-25 borders these developments to the east. The roadway network can be seen on Figure 1.
The Arapahoe Station development, which is just north of Village Center, is planned to include
approximately 38,430 square feet of retail space, 270 apartment units, and 498,000 square feet
of office space. The Village Center development is expected to contain 26,950 square feet of
retail space, 40 luxury condominium units, and 200 hotel rooms. These uses would be adjacent
to the existing Plaza Tower One office building.
Access to the proposed developments would be provided via several locations along Fiddlers
Green Circle. Arapahoe Station is planned to have two full movement accesses to Fiddlers
Green Circle. On-street, angled parking would be provided along the east side of Fiddlers Green
Circle for the proposed retail uses.
Village Center is expected to use the existing full movement access and the existing right-
in/right-out (RIRO) access on Fiddlers Green Parkway. An existing parking garage access from
Yosemite Street currently serves the Plaza Tower One, and would continue to do so in the

developments and to determine any resultant roadway improvements. This report includes
information on existing traffic conditions, trip generation associated with the planned
developments, background traffic volume projections, and total traffic volume projections. Three

Existing land uses surrounding the development site consist primarily of office uses with some
residential developments in the area. Coors Amphitheater, which hosts concerts and events
during the summer, is directly to the west of this site. An existing RTD light rail station is situated
immediately adjacent to the site along I-25.

In addition, 24-hour traffic counts were conducted along Fiddlers Green Circle just north of
Peakview Avenue and just to the west of the Arapahoe Station site. As shown, the existing daily
volumes along this roadway are about 3,150 to 5,310 vehicles per day (VPD).
Traffic operations within the study area were evaluated based on techniques documented in the
Highway Capacity Manual, (Transportation Research Board, 2000) using the existing traffic
volumes and intersection geometry. Level of Service (LOS) is a qualitative measure of traffic
operational conditions based on roadway capacity and vehicle delay. LOS is described by a
letter designation ranging from A to F, with LOS A representing generally free-flow travel, while
LOS F represents congested conditions. For signalized intersections, LOS is calculated for the
entire intersection, while LOS for unsignalized intersections is calculated for movements which
must yield right-of-way to other traffic movements.
Figure 2 shows the results of the existing conditions analysis, existing traffic control, and
current intersection geometry. Both the signalized and unsignalized intersections within the
study area currently operate at LOS C or better during both peak hours. LOS worksheets for the
existing conditions can be found in Appendix B.

Due to the mixed uses in each of these developments, the site trip generation estimates were
reduced by five percent to account for the internal trips that would occur between the
residences, office, and retail space within the proposed developments. For this analysis, both
developments were treated as one large, mixed use development. ITE methods for internal trip
reductions were used. In addition, since a light rail station is immediately adjacent to these
properties, a 15 percent reduction was applied to account for transit use, based on ITE data.

Background traffic represents the component of roadway volumes unrelated to the proposed

traffic volumes. These studies, entitled Peakview Place Traffic Impact Analysis and Centennial
Grand Traffic Impact Analysis, were prepared by Felsburg Holt & Ullevig in February 2007 and
October 2006 respectively. Trips generated by these sites have been incorporated into the
background traffic for each of the future scenarios. In addition, a hotel and an office complex
(Palazzo Verdi) planned to be constructed directly west of Fiddlers Green Circle near Arapahoe
Station have been included in the background traffic.

To address background traffic operations LOS analyses were conducted using the techniques
from the HCM-2000. The projected lane geometry, traffic control, and levels of service for each

i.b: Short Term Future (Design Year 1) Total Traffic Conditions

page.text: The site generated traffic volumes on Figure 4 were added to the Design Year 1 background
traffic volumes on Figure 6 to obtain the Design Year 1 total traffic conditions found on Figure
9. It can be seen that future daily traffic volumes on Fiddlers Green Circle are projected to range
between approximately 6,575 and 13,295 VPD adjacent to the site.
Figure 10 shows the proposed lane geometry, traffic control, and levels of service for the
Design Year 1 scenario. The same lane and traffic control recommendations made for the
background traffic conditions also apply to the build condition. As can be seen on this figure,
most of the stop controlled approaches at the site accesses and the signalized intersections are
projected to operate at LOS D or better with the lane geometry and traffic control shown. The
only exceptions are the outbound left turns at each of the full movement site accesses, which
are projected to operate at LOS E during the PM peak hour. Based on Warrant 3 (Peak Hour),
Manual on Uniform Traffic Control Devices (MUTCD), none of the three full-movement accesses
would warrant a traffic signal in Design Year 1. As an interim improvement, the Village Center
full-movement access could be provided all-way STOP sign control. Traffic operations would be
at LOS C or D during peak times.
At the Fiddlers Green Circle/Peakview Avenue intersection, dual left-turn lanes would be
required on the southbound approach. Typically, dual left-turn lanes are indicated when the
associated movement exceeds 300 vehicles per hour (VPH); the projected left-turn movement
would be approximately 755 VPH in the PM peak hour.

from the previously described trip generation analysis, as summarized in Table 4.

As indicated, the retail component of development at Arapahoe Station would generate
approximately 1,650 trips on a daily basis, with about 40 AM peak hour trips and about 145 PM
peak hour trips. These estimates include the reductions for on-site interaction and proximity to
As a means to approximate the potential traffic operational conditions associated with this on-
street parking, LOS calculations were conducted. The analyses were based on the outbound
retail traffic volumes from Table 4 in combination with the conflicting westbound through-
volumes projected for Fiddlers Green Circle (extracted from the Design Year 20 Total Traffic
conditions). The through-volumes would be about 1,085 vehicles per hour during the AM peak
hour and about 495 vehicles per hour during the PM peak hour.
During the AM peak hour, vehicles backing out into traffic along Fiddlers Green Circle would
experience an average delay of about 26 seconds before finding an acceptable gap in traffic.
This condition corresponds to LOS D, and is within the range of acceptability for peak hour
operations. During the PM peak hour, the parking maneuver would experience an average
delay of about 15 seconds, corresponding to LOS C; again within the acceptable range.
Safety is an important consideration for on-street parking operations. Studies have shown that
streets with parking have an increased frequency of accidents compared to streets without
parking. In the case of angle parking, vehicles must back out into traffic flow, sometimes with
reduced or impaired sight distance. However, the potential for increased accidents along
Fiddlers Green Circle may be mitigated by the following measures:
• The proposed nearby traffic signals at the Village Center access and the north Arapahoe
Station access would help to slow traffic along Fiddlers Green Circle. Lower vehicle
speeds would enhance driver reaction and reduce potential accident severity. The
proposed traffic signals would also help provide gaps in traffic for parking maneuvers.
• The current site plan concept for Arapahoe Station would maintain a 26 foot wide travel
way along Fiddlers Green Circle adjacent to the proposed on-street parking. Reducing
the inside lane width to 10 or 11 feet would allow for an outside lane width of between 15
and 16 feet (3 to 4 feet wider than the standard 12 foot lane width). This additional
outside lane width could provide a buffer for increased visibility of parking maneuvers.
